Only in North America.

In medieval times an esquire was an apprentice knight, who acted as a kind of
personal assistant and gofer, carried his equipment etc.  The word comes from
the Latin  &quot;scutum&quot; = shield, and refers to a shield bearer.

Later in England it was used for minor gentry, and for a time was used by
status seekers as a substitute for Mr, coming after a man's name instead of
before.

As a book called &quot;Titles and forms of address: a guide to their correct use&quot;
laments:

&quot;The almost universal use of this title for every man who cannot claim a
higher one persists in spite of protests and objections from those who are
really entitled to it.&quot;

Those who are really entitled to it are &quot;Companions&quot; of various orders of
Knighthood, whose members, in order of precedence are &quot;Knights Grand Cross&quot;,
&quot;Knights Commanders&quot; and &quot;Companions&quot;. The first two have &quot;Sir&quot; before their
name, and the last have &quot;Esq.&quot; after.

Sir Robert Johnson G.C.M.G. (Knight Grand Cross of the Most Distinguished Oder
of St Michael and St George).

Richard Jackson, Esq., C.M.G. (Companion of the Most Distinguished Order of St
Michael and St George).

The main solecism was to use both Mr and Esq.

You either addressed a letter to

John Smith Esq.
or
Mr John Smith

but never, never, ever

Mr John Smith Esq.

I have a friend who still likes to be addressed as Esq., and he also wears a
monocle, which shows what kind of stone he crawled out from under. He was
never a Companion of anything.

It belongs to the age when toilets were labeled &quot;ladies&quot; and &quot;gents&quot;.

Anyway, my dictionary says it is a tile of respect, generally abbreviated
Esq., placed after a man's name.

But in 1809 he may indeed have been a gent.

