Not quite as simply as that. Yeoman in the C16,C17, the early C18 meant he owned
his land, but by the late C18 and after, it was equally applied to a big farmer who
might be a major tenant. It was then the size of the holding, not the free status,
which applied. And 'gentleman' even after 1800 rarely applied to a farmer or
tradesman who dirtied his hands - not till he retired (since you had to be rich to retire
anyway.)
