Forms of address change over time and with circumstances. The general
answer for all such enquiries as the meaning of Esq is 'Get into the
mindsets and social structure of the time.' There is no invariant
meaning.

In the case of Esq, a person who uses it to another would probably be
regarded as fawning and a boot-licker. A person who insists on it
being used for themselves would probably be regarded as a pretentious
prat.

It can be edgy for some older people, such as me, who have lived
through changes of etiquette. It seems odd to address a bishop as
Christopher during a church event although there is hardly a more
logical case and time for using a 'christian' name for a person.

In my era it was possible for a graduate of KCL to refer to himself as
a 'King's man', but not permissible to refer to any other male
graduate in that way. They were 'King's gentlemen'. There was no such
thing as a 'King's woman' since that had rather unfortunate
connotations. They were all 'King's ladies'. Postdocs couldn't be
referred to as gentlemen or ladies, they had to be 'eminent' gentlemen
or ladies. It sounds incredible in modern parlance but it was the rule
50 years and more ago.

Then there are the different rules in other cultures which sound weird
when translated literally into English. I get communications in
impeccable English, except for one thing, from an elderly lady
colleague in Berlin. The one thing she cannot seem to do is cease
using the German form of address.

We won't go into the hysterics which arise when certain Latin cultures
try to get round Don as both honorific and name.

The problem when looking at old records is that the terms and the
etiquette for using them are not explained. At the time, no
explanation was necessary since they were hat was accepted as correct.
Many people, got and get stroppy if addressed in a way which does not
comply with prevailing etiquette. Try dealing with high-ranking
Japanese in the modern sloppy manner of most western business culture.

Don
